00012 /*
00013 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00014 mix -- mix 3 32-bit values reversibly.
00015 For every delta with one or two bit set, and the deltas of all three
00016   high bits or all three low bits, whether the original value of a,b,c
00017   is almost all zero or is uniformly distributed,
00018 * If mix() is run forward or backward, at least 32 bits in a,b,c
00019   have at least 1/4 probability of changing.
00020 * If mix() is run forward, every bit of c will change between 1/3 and
00021   2/3 of the time.  (Well, 22/100 and 78/100 for some 2-bit deltas.)
00022 mix() was built out of 36 single-cycle latency instructions in a 
00023   structure that could supported 2x parallelism, like so:
00024       a -= b; 
00025       a -= c; x = (c>>13);
00026       b -= c; a ^= x;
00027       b -= a; x = (a<<8);
00028       c -= a; b ^= x;
00029       c -= b; x = (b>>13);
00030       ...
00031   Unfortunately, superscalar Pentiums and Sparcs can't take advantage 
00032   of that parallelism.  They've also turned some of those single-cycle
00033   latency instructions into multi-cycle latency instructions.  Still,
00034   this is the fastest good hash I could find.  There were about 2^^68
00035   to choose from.  I only looked at a billion or so.
00036 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00037 */
00038 #define mix(a,b,c) \
00039 { \
00040   a -= b; a -= c; a ^= (c>>13); \
00041   b -= c; b -= a; b ^= (a<<8); \
00042   c -= a; c -= b; c ^= (b>>13); \
00043   a -= b; a -= c; a ^= (c>>12);  \
00044   b -= c; b -= a; b ^= (a<<16); \
00045   c -= a; c -= b; c ^= (b>>5); \
00046   a -= b; a -= c; a ^= (c>>3);  \
00047   b -= c; b -= a; b ^= (a<<10); \
00048   c -= a; c -= b; c ^= (b>>15); \
00049 }

00051 /*
00052 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00053 lookup() -- hash a variable-length key into a 32-bit value
00054   k     : the key (the unaligned variable-length array of bytes)
00055   len   : the length of the key, counting by bytes
00056   level : can be any 4-byte value
00057 Returns a 32-bit value.  Every bit of the key affects every bit of
00058 the return value.  Every 1-bit and 2-bit delta achieves avalanche.
00059 About 6len+35 instructions.
00060 
00061 The best hash table sizes are powers of 2.  There is no need to do
00062 mod a prime (mod is sooo slow!).  If you need less than 32 bits,
00063 use a bitmask.  For example, if you need only 10 bits, do
00064   h = (h & hashmask(10));
00065 In which case, the hash table should have hashsize(10) elements.
00066 
00067 If you are hashing n strings (ub1 **)k, do it like this:
00068   for (i=0, h=0; i<n; ++i) h = lookup( k[i], len[i], h);
00069 
00070 By Bob Jenkins, 1996.  bob_jenkins@burtleburtle.net.  You may use this
00071 code any way you wish, private, educational, or commercial.
00072 
00073 See http://burtleburtle.net/bob/hash/evahash.html
00074 Use for hash table lookup, or anything where one collision in 2^32 is
00075 acceptable.  Do NOT use for cryptographic purposes.
00076 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00077 */
00078 
00079 ub4 lookup( k, length, level)
00080 register ub1 *k;        /* the key */
00081 register ub4  length;   /* the length of the key */
00082 register ub4  level;    /* the previous hash, or an arbitrary value */
00083 {
00084    register ub4 a,b,c,len;
00085 
00086    /* Set up the internal state */
00087    len = length;
00088    a = b = 0x9e3779b9;  /* the golden ratio; an arbitrary value */
00089    c = level;           /* the previous hash value */
00090 
00091    /*---------------------------------------- handle most of the key */
00092    while (len >= 12)
00093    {
00094       a += (k[0] +((ub4)k[1]<<8) +((ub4)k[2]<<16) +((ub4)k[3]<<24));
00095       b += (k[4] +((ub4)k[5]<<8) +((ub4)k[6]<<16) +((ub4)k[7]<<24));
00096       c += (k[8] +((ub4)k[9]<<8) +((ub4)k[10]<<16)+((ub4)k[11]<<24));
00097       mix(a,b,c);
00098       k += 12; len -= 12;
00099    }
00100 
00101    /*------------------------------------- handle the last 11 bytes */
00102    c += length;
00103    switch(len)              /* all the case statements fall through */
00104    {
00105    case 11: c+=((ub4)k[10]<<24);
00106    case 10: c+=((ub4)k[9]<<16);
00107    case 9 : c+=((ub4)k[8]<<8);
00108       /* the first byte of c is reserved for the length */
00109    case 8 : b+=((ub4)k[7]<<24);
00110    case 7 : b+=((ub4)k[6]<<16);
00111    case 6 : b+=((ub4)k[5]<<8);
00112    case 5 : b+=k[4];
00113    case 4 : a+=((ub4)k[3]<<24);
00114    case 3 : a+=((ub4)k[2]<<16);
00115    case 2 : a+=((ub4)k[1]<<8);
00116    case 1 : a+=k[0];
00117      /* case 0: nothing left to add */
00118    }
00119    mix(a,b,c);
00120    /*-------------------------------------------- report the result */
00121    return c;
00122 }

00125 /*
00126 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00127 mixc -- mixc 8 4-bit values as quickly and thoroughly as possible.
00128 Repeating mix() three times achieves avalanche.
00129 Repeating mix() four times eliminates all funnels and all
00130   characteristics stronger than 2^{-11}.
00131 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00132 */
00133 #define mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h) \
00134 { \
00135    a^=b<<11; d+=a; b+=c; \
00136    b^=c>>2;  e+=b; c+=d; \
00137    c^=d<<8;  f+=c; d+=e; \
00138    d^=e>>16; g+=d; e+=f; \
00139    e^=f<<10; h+=e; f+=g; \
00140    f^=g>>4;  a+=f; g+=h; \
00141    g^=h<<8;  b+=g; h+=a; \
00142    h^=a>>9;  c+=h; a+=b; \
00143 }

00145 /*
00146 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00147 checksum() -- hash a variable-length key into a 256-bit value
00148   k     : the key (the unaligned variable-length array of bytes)
00149   len   : the length of the key, counting by bytes
00150   state : an array of CHECKSTATE 4-byte values (256 bits)
00151 The state is the checksum.  Every bit of the key affects every bit of
00152 the state.  There are no funnels.  About 112+6.875len instructions.
00153 
00154 If you are hashing n strings (ub1 **)k, do it like this:
00155   for (i=0; i<8; ++i) state[i] = 0x9e3779b9;
00156   for (i=0, h=0; i<n; ++i) checksum( k[i], len[i], state);
00157 
00158 See http://burtleburtle.net/bob/hash/evahash.html
00159 Use to detect changes between revisions of documents, assuming nobody
00160 is trying to cause collisions.  Do NOT use for cryptography.
00161 --------------------------------------------------------------------
00162 */
00163 void  checksum( k, len, state)
00164 register ub1 *k;
00165 register ub4  len;
00166 register ub4 *state;
00167 {
00168    register ub4 a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h,length;
00169 
00170    /* Use the length and level; add in the golden ratio. */
00171    length = len;
00172    a=state[0]; b=state[1]; c=state[2]; d=state[3];
00173    e=state[4]; f=state[5]; g=state[6]; h=state[7];
00174 
00175    /*---------------------------------------- handle most of the key */
00176    while (len >= 32)
00177    {
00178       a += (k[0] +(k[1]<<8) +(k[2]<<16) +(k[3]<<24));
00179       b += (k[4] +(k[5]<<8) +(k[6]<<16) +(k[7]<<24));
00180       c += (k[8] +(k[9]<<8) +(k[10]<<16)+(k[11]<<24));
00181       d += (k[12]+(k[13]<<8)+(k[14]<<16)+(k[15]<<24));
00182       e += (k[16]+(k[17]<<8)+(k[18]<<16)+(k[19]<<24));
00183       f += (k[20]+(k[21]<<8)+(k[22]<<16)+(k[23]<<24));
00184       g += (k[24]+(k[25]<<8)+(k[26]<<16)+(k[27]<<24));
00185       h += (k[28]+(k[29]<<8)+(k[30]<<16)+(k[31]<<24));
00186       mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00187       mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00188       mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00189       mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00190       k += 32; len -= 32;
00191    }
00192 
00193    /*------------------------------------- handle the last 31 bytes */
00194    h += length;
00195    switch(len)
00196    {
00197    case 31: h+=(k[30]<<24);
00198    case 30: h+=(k[29]<<16);
00199    case 29: h+=(k[28]<<8);
00200    case 28: g+=(k[27]<<24);
00201    case 27: g+=(k[26]<<16);
00202    case 26: g+=(k[25]<<8);
00203    case 25: g+=k[24];
00204    case 24: f+=(k[23]<<24);
00205    case 23: f+=(k[22]<<16);
00206    case 22: f+=(k[21]<<8);
00207    case 21: f+=k[20];
00208    case 20: e+=(k[19]<<24);
00209    case 19: e+=(k[18]<<16);
00210    case 18: e+=(k[17]<<8);
00211    case 17: e+=k[16];
00212    case 16: d+=(k[15]<<24);
00213    case 15: d+=(k[14]<<16);
00214    case 14: d+=(k[13]<<8);
00215    case 13: d+=k[12];
00216    case 12: c+=(k[11]<<24);
00217    case 11: c+=(k[10]<<16);
00218    case 10: c+=(k[9]<<8);
00219    case 9 : c+=k[8];
00220    case 8 : b+=(k[7]<<24);
00221    case 7 : b+=(k[6]<<16);
00222    case 6 : b+=(k[5]<<8);
00223    case 5 : b+=k[4];
00224    case 4 : a+=(k[3]<<24);
00225    case 3 : a+=(k[2]<<16);
00226    case 2 : a+=(k[1]<<8);
00227    case 1 : a+=k[0];
00228    }
00229    mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00230    mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00231    mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00232    mixc(a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h);
00233 
00234    /*-------------------------------------------- report the result */
00235    state[0]=a; state[1]=b; state[2]=c; state[3]=d;
00236    state[4]=e; state[5]=f; state[6]=g; state[7]=h;
00237 }

00240 ub4 jenkins_one_at_a_time_hash(ub1 *key, size_t len)
00241 {
00242     ub4 hash, i;
00243     for(hash = i = 0; i < len; ++i)
00244     {
00245         hash += key[i];
00246         hash += (hash << 10);
00247         hash ^= (hash >> 6);
00248     }
00249     hash += (hash << 3);
00250     hash ^= (hash >> 11);
00251     hash += (hash << 15);
00252     return hash;
00253 }
